Collections Class

1. What is the Collections class in Java?
-->The Collections class is a utility class present in the java.util package. It provides static methods to perform various operations 
    on Collection objects such as sorting, searching, reversing, shuffling, finding minimum/maximum elements, creating synchronized collections,
    and creating unmodifiable collections.

Example:

import java.util.*;

List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(5, 2, 8, 1);

Collections.sort(list);

System.out.println(list);

Output

[1, 2, 5, 8]




2. What is the difference between Collection and Collections?
-->
| Collection                      | Collections                               |
| ------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| Interface                       | Utility Class                             |
| Present in `java.util`          | Present in `java.util`                    |
| Used to store groups of objects | Used to perform operations on collections |
| Implemented by List, Set, Queue | Contains only static methods              |
| Example: ArrayList, HashSet     | Example: sort(), reverse(), shuffle()     |

Interview Tip:

Collection → Interface
Collections → Utility class



3. What are some important methods of the Collections class?
-->Some commonly used methods are:
| Method                         | Purpose                      |
| ------------------------------ | ---------------------------- |
| Collections.sort()             | Sorts a list                 |
| Collections.reverse()          | Reverses list                |
| Collections.shuffle()          | Randomly shuffles elements   |
| Collections.binarySearch()     | Searches an element          |
| Collections.min()              | Finds minimum element        |
| Collections.max()              | Finds maximum element        |
| Collections.frequency()        | Counts occurrences           |
| Collections.copy()             | Copies one list into another |
