4. What does Collections.sort() do? How is Collections.sort() different from List.sort()?
-->Collections.sort()

Sorts a list in ascending order.

List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(5,1,3);

Collections.sort(list);

System.out.println(list);

Output

[1,3,5]

Difference :
| Collections.sort()         | List.sort()             |
| -------------------------- | ----------------------- |
| Static method              | Default method (Java 8) |
| Utility class              | List interface          |
| Uses Comparable/Comparator | Uses Comparator         |
| Available before Java 8    | Introduced in Java 8    |

Example:

list.sort(Comparator.reverseOrder());



5. How does Collections.reverse() work?
-->It reverses the order of elements in a list.

Example:

List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(1,2,3,4);

Collections.reverse(list);

System.out.println(list);

Output

[4,3,2,1]

Time Complexity: O(n)




6. How to find min() and max() using Collections?
-->Example:

        List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(4,8,2,6);
        
        System.out.println(Collections.min(list));
        System.out.println(Collections.max(list));
        
        Output
        
        2
        8
        
        Works with:
        
        Comparable
        Comparator
        
        Example:
        
        Collections.max(list, Comparator.naturalOrder());






7. What does Collections.binarySearch() do?
-->Performs Binary Search on a sorted list.

Time Complexity

O(log n)

Example:

List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(10,20,30,40);

int index = Collections.binarySearch(list,30);

System.out.println(index);

Output

2

If not found:

Collections.binarySearch(list,25);

Returns

-(Insertion Point)-1

Example output

-3




8. What does Collections.frequency() do?
-->Returns the number of occurrences of an element.

Example:

List<String> list = Arrays.asList("A","B","A","C","A");

System.out.println(Collections.frequency(list,"A"));

Output

3





9. What is the purpose of Collections.copy()?
-->Copies all elements from one list to another.

Destination list must already have enough size.

Example:

List<String> src = Arrays.asList("A","B","C");

List<String> dest = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("X","Y","Z"));

Collections.copy(dest,src);

System.out.println(dest);

Output

[A, B, C]







10. How do you make a collection thread-safe? By using Collections.synchronizedList(), Collections.synchronizedSet(), 
and Collections.synchronizedMap()?
-->Collections provides synchronized wrappers.

List
List<Integer> list =
Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<>());
Set
Set<Integer> set =
Collections.synchronizedSet(new HashSet<>());
Map
Map<Integer,String> map =
Collections.synchronizedMap(new HashMap<>());

These wrappers make collections thread-safe for concurrent access.



11. How do you make a collection read-only (unmodifiable)?
-->Using unmodifiable methods.

Example:

List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(1,2,3);

List<Integer> readOnly =
Collections.unmodifiableList(list);

Trying to modify:

readOnly.add(10);

Throws

UnsupportedOperationException

Similarly:

Collections.unmodifiableSet()
Collections.unmodifiableMap()






12. What does Collections.disjoint() do?
-->Checks whether two collections have no common elements.

Returns:

true → No common elements
false → Common elements exist

Example:

List<Integer> a = Arrays.asList(1,2,3);

List<Integer> b = Arrays.asList(4,5,6);

System.out.println(Collections.disjoint(a,b));

Output

true

Another example:

List<Integer> c = Arrays.asList(3,4,5);

System.out.println(Collections.disjoint(a,c));

Output

false





13. What's the difference between Collections.emptyList() and Collections.singletonList()?
-->
| Collections.emptyList()         | Collections.singletonList()                |
| ------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| Returns an immutable empty list | Returns an immutable list with one element |
| Size = 0                        | Size = 1                                   |
| Cannot modify                   | Cannot modify                              |


Example:

List<String> list1 = Collections.emptyList();

List<String> list2 = Collections.singletonList("Java");

System.out.println(list1);
System.out.println(list2);

Output

[]
[Java]


Interview Tips :

    Collections is a utility class with only static methods.
    Collection is an interface.
    Collections.sort() sorts lists in ascending order.
    Collections.binarySearch() works only on sorted lists.
    Collections.reverse() reverses the order of elements.
    Collections.frequency() counts occurrences of an element.
    Collections.copy() requires the destination list to be pre-sized.
    Collections.disjoint() checks if two collections have no common elements.
    Collections.synchronizedList(), synchronizedSet(), and synchronizedMap() provide thread-safe wrappers.
    Collections.unmodifiableList() creates a read-only view of a collection.
    Collections.emptyList() returns an immutable empty list, while Collections.singletonList() returns an immutable list containing exactly one element.



